node.text:
The local trade association estimates that more than 400,000 vehicles suffered water damage in last month's flood in Zhengzhou, China.

Photos show one of the lots where damaged cars have been towed. Row after row of cars, many of which will need to be discarded entirely, sit to wait out their fate.

On July 20, the already waterlogged Zhengzhou was inundated with 8 inches of rain in just one hour. The rapid rainfall turned roads into rivers, washing away hundreds of thousands of vehicles, trapping children in schools, and stranding workers overnight in their workplaces. Earlier this month, according to the Henan provincial government, the flood's death toll reached 302. The majority of the victims were in Zhengzhou.

Click the link in our bio to see more photos of the fields of damaged cars in Zhengzhou.

Photo by Feature China/Barcroft Media via Getty Images

node.text:
What’s left of Greenville, California, after the Dixie Fire ravaged the Gold Rush era town? Not much. The fire destroyed about 75% of the town, and all of the downtown area, burning homes, businesses and schools. Historic buildings that were built in the late 1800s are now reduced to ash and rubble.

The Dixie Fire is now considered California’s largest single fire in state history, though it’s only about half the size of the August Complex Fire, a series of related fires that burned up about 1,613 square miles in the state in August 2020. 

The Dixie Fire has burned more than 762 square miles since its ignition on July 13. That's an area larger than the city of Los Angeles. As of Tuesday, the fire is only 25% contained.

The photos above show Greenville locations before and during the fire next to what they looked like after the blaze. Click the link in our bio to see more of the dramatic images.

Photos by Josh Edelson/Getty Images

#DixieFire #Greenville #wildfire

node.text:
A disturbance in the eastern Caribbean Sea is likely to soon become Tropical Storm Fred as it brings heavy rain and gusty winds to parts of the Caribbean Islands over the next few days. Beyond the Caribbean, it's uncertain what, if any, impacts this system might bring to Florida during the weekend ahead, but parts of the state are in the forecast cone as of Tuesday morning.

The National Hurricane Center (NHC) has designated a low-pressure system spreading showers and thunderstorms into the eastern Caribbean Sea as "Potential Tropical Cyclone Six.”

This "potential tropical cyclone" procedure allows the NHC to issue watches and warnings ahead of time for a system that hasn't become well organized enough to be deemed a tropical depression or storm, but is forecast to become one.

The official forecast from the NHC shows that this system is likely to develop into Tropical Storm Fred on Tuesday as it moves generally toward the west-northwest.
